They value individualistic approaches to justice and social structures rather than blaming inequality on others[4]. Susan Wendell argues: “The clearest political commitments of liberal feminism, including equality of opportunity, are essential to women's liberation and are not at all compatible with the goals of socialist and radical feminism. '[4]. The foundation of liberalism has given liberal feminism a well-known basis for being closer than other waves to convince the general public and government that their feminist philosophy "can and should be incorporated into existing law"[5]. How states Ryan Musgrave: “Liberal feminists advocated the legal inclusion of women in the liberal category of the individual as a basic social unit, and that women should also enjoy the individual rights associated with this category” [6]. Also, quite a few American liberal feminists believe that equality pay, job opportunities arrangement, political structure, welfare and education for women especially should be guaranteed by the US Constitution.